The Economy of Violence
COPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine, and elsewhere are constantly in the news and therefore many would probably say war.
But that proves to be a great mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-effective solutions for this and other global problems.
It goes without saying that everyone would gladly end war and violence, just as we would gladly put an end to poverty, hunger, and global warming and ensure that all people have access to education.
Yet, given limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We must set priorities, and for that, one can use an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to assess which goals, in their view, would be the wisest.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the use of resources that could otherwise, for example, be spent on fighting hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon of Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at the University of Oxford, violence within society—murders and especially violence against women and children—presents a far greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die as a result of interpersonal violence, and for every two fighters who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and far too many countries report murder rates of more than 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization refers to as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs one person's life and society 9.1 million US dollars.
Measured against global national income, this form of violent crime alone costs 1.7% of global gross social product (GDP).
Of course, this is not a direct financial loss for the world economy, but rather a way to express the consequences.
If murders could be abolished, societies around the world would be in a better position in a way that can be measured in 1.7% of GDP.
Compare this with the significantly lower costs of civil wars, which amount to about 0.2% of global GDP.
That is still, however, much less than the greatest source of violence altogether: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence from their life partners or family members in the past year.
These include women who were beaten, married off at a young age, exposed to sexual violence, and subjected to crimes in the name of "honor" and female genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal consequences of violence by partners alone amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars or 5.2% of global GDP.
The second largest source of violence is the maltreatment of children, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of what constitutes child abuse varies from culture to culture, but approximately 15% of children experience each month what the UN describes as severe physical punishment.
These include slaps to the face, head, or ears, and a quarter of these children are repeatedly and as forcefully as possible struck with an object.
Every month, this suffering affects approximately 290 million children.
The social costs amount to 3.6 trillion US dollars or 4.2% of global GDP.
Only a tiny fraction of international aid money is currently flowing into the reduction of violence in society and the improvement of criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and individuals demand immediate action.
Unfortunately, there are still hardly any reliable insights as to where the limited resources should best be used.
All that can be said is that the money spent on reducing violence could be better targeted.
Large sums of aid money are earmarked for "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the "crime prevention" component.
Other programs can certainly contribute indirectly, but obviously much could be improved.
Some solutions, as is clear, work very well.
More capable social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the U.S. state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve children's quality of life and their physical and mental health, and lower the costs of care and legal proceedings.
A dollar spent on this program produces a benefit worth 14 US dollars: it is thus an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program in Uganda called SASA! is working.
(Swahili for "Now!") to spread the message that violence in relationships is unacceptable and has contributed to halving the number of cases.
That is a fantastic result, even though there is no analysis of cost-effectiveness available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures are being taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach – setting a time limit for alcohol sales, reclaiming public space, and improving the police and justice system – the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004.
That is still a high number, but far below Detroit's murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 inhabitants.
Alcohol plays a role in many lethal attacks, and the insights from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of major importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on the better enforcement of existing regulations showed that lethal attacks could be reduced in a very cost-effective manner, with the benefits outweighing the costs by a ratio of 17 to 1.
We still do not know enough, but two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children brings annual societal costs of 8 trillion US dollars and thus represents a huge - and far too little noticed - global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can help address some of these problems in a very cost-effective way.
Therefore, the reduction of domestic violence should be among the priorities for the next global development goals.
